Momas Electricity Meter Manufacturing Company (MEMMCOL) and the National Agency for Science and Engineering Infrastructure (NASENI) have signed a Memorandum of Understanding on the development of smart prepaid meters. A statement by MEMMCOL said the agreement was signed by its Chairman Mr Kola Balogun, and Executive Vice Chairman of NASENI, Prof. Mohammed Haruna, in Abuja. Balogun said the partnership would help to address the metering challenges in the Nigeria Electricity Supply Industry (NESI). He said: “The terms of reference is that we collaborate and synergise to develop local capability on meters and some other technology inclined devices that will be useful for the nation. “Essentially, it is to develop the first set of meters that will address the incoming Internet of Things (IoT) smart meters. “This meter will make energy more accountable. It will be consumer-friendly, ease revenue collection and monitoring of power theft in the sector.”   Banks demand $91.4m from BEDC, others     Elegushi urges prayers for Nigeria     ‘Nigeria needs professional care services’   Balogun said the processes have already started and expressed optimism that the new meter would be launched before the end of the year. He said when the prototype of the meter is developed, it would serve as a standard and guide for other companies involved in meter manufacturing in Nigeria. “This will be a more modern type of meter and will address all the peculiarities being faced currently by prepaid meter users. “We believe this is an opportunity to close to the huge metering gap in the country which is one of the problems bedevilling the power sector,” Balogun said. Haruna said NASENI was committed to partnering with the company in areas of meter installation, training design, maintenance, amongst others. He said NASENI’s mandate was to collaborate with organisations like MOMAS for national development and job creation.